of the humerus, and inserts into the pisiform and hook of the hamate","Originates from the medial epicondyle of the humerus, and inserts into the base of the first metacarpal","Originates from the lateral epicondyle of the humerus, and inserts into the base of the second metacarpal","Originates from the olecranon of the ulna, and inserts into the base of the third metacarpal"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexor carpi ulnaris (FCU)\u003C/strong\u003E is a muscle of the forearm that primarily functions to flex and adduct the wrist. It originates from two heads: the medial epicondyle of the humerus and the olecranon of the ulna. The FCU inserts into the pisiform, hook of the hamate, and base of the fifth metacarpal. This anatomical configuration allows it to perform its function effectively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option stating that the FCU \u003Cstrong\u003Eoriginates from the lateral epicondyle of the humerus and inserts into the base of the second metacarpal\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as this describes the extensor carpi radialis longus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option stating that the FCU \u003Cstrong\u003Eoriginates from the olecranon of the ulna and inserts into the base of the third metacarpal\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as the FCU does not insert into the third metacarpal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option stating that the FCU \u003Cstrong\u003Eoriginates from the medial epicondyle of the humerus and inserts into the base of the first metacarpal\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as this describes the flexor carpi radialis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option stating that the FCU \u003Cstrong\u003Eoriginates from the lateral epicondyle of the humerus and inserts into the pisiform and hook of the hamate\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as the FCU originates from the medial epicondyle, not the lateral.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The flexor carpi ulnaris (FCU) is a muscle of the forearm that acts to flex and adduct the wrist.","The FCU originates from the medial epicondyle of the humerus and the olecranon of the ulna.","The FCU inserts into the pisiform, hook of the hamate, and base of the fifth metacarpal."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Raszewski JA, Black AC, Launico MV, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Hand Compartments. [Updated 2023 Oct 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK532942/","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences250"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65983"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18154"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65983"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-22T11:17:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T11:18:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10868"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80685"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"se